This paper deals with the problem of morphological processing, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP). The paper proposes a language-independent approach that uses a Directed Acyclic Word Graph (DAWG) to store lemmas, inflected forms, and grammatical features. This approach can be applied to any language, making it relevant to the sub-category of NLP represented by cs.CL (Computation and Language). The use of a DAWG also involves graph theory, which is relevant to the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also mentions the use of incremental construction algorithms, which are relevant to the sub-category of cs.LG (Learning). Additionally, the paper's approach does not rely on any pre-programmed linguistic information, which suggests the use of machine learning techniques, making it relevant to the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval).
